### Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle

If a measurement of position is made with uncertainty \(\Delta x\) and a simultaneous measurement of momentum is made with uncertainty \(\Delta p\). The product of the two uncertainties can never be smaller than the Planck constant

\(\Delta p\Delta x\geq h\)

The uncertainty principle limits the precision that complementary quantities (such as position along \(x\)-axis and the momentum in the \(x\) direction) can have. For example, if we know very well the position along the \(x\)-axis of a particle (\(\Delta x\) is very small), then we cannot be very certain what momentum in the \(x\)-direction the particle possesses, since \(\Delta p\approx h/\Delta x\) is huge if \(\Delta x\) is very small. Note that this has nothing to do with the precision of the apparatus/method used to perform the measurements. The uncertainty principle is a fundamental principle of nature. However, we may still know \(p_{\gamma}\) or \(p_{z}\) very well, even if we know the \(x\) position very well, since the uncertainty principle applies only to position and momentum along the same direction.

